BoW i assume via superior DPS and proc rate helps to ensure the warrior keeps aggro well - perhaps the aggro generation from the DPS is even high enough that the 'danger period' at the beginning of the fight when slow can outaggro is reduced making for less bouncing? Difficult to believe but theoretically possible I guess. <br>
<br>
Wether one believes that BoW removes the problems warriors face or not is actually irrelevant however. It is not possible to point to such an exclusive weapon (the best in the game at this time for a warrior) and say 'with this you're fixed'. It is no more reasonable to expect every warrior to have this weapon than it is to expect a 61 warrior to outtank a 65 SK with 100+ AA's. Fixes with itemisation <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>do not work</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> because the 'average' member of any class cannot be expected to have such an exclusive item. Even with level 65 making AoW encounters relatively less hard, BoC's and such cannot be considered as 'normal useage' weaponry for 80 - 90% of the warrior population -  and this was SoE's 'fix' of three years ago.<br>
<br>
Brik more or less admits that without EB or similar weaponry a warrior faces great problems with aggro-maintenance (a quality vital to the job of tank), yet knights for minor cost have not only snap aggro but almost assured aggro retention capabilities at the push of a button. Brik asserts that this is balanced by the mitigation and avoidance bonuses that a warrior brings to a group making for less risk of your main tank dying. This is to an extent perhaps true, but I must say that, based on my own observation of knight guildmates when grouped (with their equipment and AA's not being exceptionally better than my own) i am not seeing a very visible, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>noticable</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> difference. <br>
<br>
As an example Brik cites a situation where one or two dodges due to increased warrior avoidance saves a warrior where a knight dies. I wonder how often (with skill caps being where they are) the warriors dodge/parry/whatever skill succeeds where the knights fails? 1 time in 5?, 1 time in 10? <br>
<br>
/shrug<br>
<br>
We can perhaps increase our chance of survival via defensive/evasive or furious discipline but the knights also have special abilities they can call on to help them out. Lay on hands, Stunning the mob so he doesn't hit for the fraction of time needed for the heal to land, Discipline leechcurse, and various taps which help mitigate damage taken etc. <br>
<br>
With a good healer the above scenario should not even occur with any frequency in the first place.<br>
<br>
The assertion that warriors are favoured for tanking elemental exp mobs is beyond my in game experience but is somewhat weakened by the posts of another experienced knight (Iustus) in which he asserts that knights are perfectly acceptable tanks in the elementals. One would think the ability to slow early (with negligable risk of pingpong) would be particularly favoured given the damage output of said mobs. <br>
<br>
In any case SoE has basically stated that there will be no access quests to tier 3-4 zones making them the exclusive property of hard core raid guilds - and thus removing them from the equation when balancing the 'average' warrior against the 'average' knight.<br>
<br>
At the current time knights have an extremely obvious advantage in aggro generation, whilst warriors have (when facing high DPS PoP mobs) what appears to me to be only a very marginal mitigation/avoidance advantage. <br>
<br>
The other thing we have working in our favour is that it is a habit with people to let the warrior tank. It does appear though, that more and more people (assuming one believes the various posts on other class boards) are now coming to the conclusion that the knights better aggro control actually makes for a safer, more hassle free, more healer-mana efficient, group experience. <br>
<br>
If that view becomes prevalent then warriors will become nearly as badly off as knights were in the Kunark era (with the exception that they will still be dragged out of semi-retirement to tank some boss mobs on raids). This is a possibility that I am not keen to see happen.<br>
<br>
Increasing our mitigation advantage is not a viable route to take. The speed with which PoP mobs strip the hitpoints from a tank means that it would require a ludicrous amount of additional hp's to really show a visibly superior mitigation rate. Giving warriors such hp totals would break a massive amount of content/encounters.<br>
<br>
Brik asserts that giving warriors some form of burst aggro similar to a knight (to offset the initial aggro generation problem) would ensure knights were banished back to their kunark era ignominy. I have to question that assumption.<br>
<br>
Knights are in nowhere near the same position relative to a warrior as they were in kunark times. Knights are perfectly able to tank a mob in an exp group without serious disadvantage or requiring noticeably more healing.<br>
<br>
Additionally, I would argue that the various extra abilities they have <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>do</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> bring other advantages to a group (cily above goes so far as to state that they will still be preferred for groups because of this - still not sure wether he's actually a knight or not though <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     ). In one afternoon i heard a guildmate monk state that shadowknights were in his opinion a better choice to split pull in PoP and a shaman friend was telling me she felt paladins provided more to the group than her as (secondary? i'm not totally clear on what she meant) healers.<br>
<br>
These abilities might not be massive in their impact and perhaps they wouldn't garantee a spot in a group determined to absolutely maximise it's potential but they would still be an incentive over and above what a warrior would bring to a group. Particularly if that group was looking for more and already had a tank of some description.<br>
 <br>
Given knights much improved viability, would reducing (<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>not</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> eliminating) the difference between knight and warrior aggro truely be as disasterous as Brik proposes? <br>
<br>
Hmm,<br>
<br>
